]]></fr:tex>
                <fr:p>We will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for the <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> matching or “recognised” by the regular expression <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}} =
 {\mathopen {}\left \{
  u\in \Sigma ^\star 
  \mid 
  u\mathrel {\textsf {matches}}R
 \right \}\mathclose {}}
]]></fr:tex>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>We can also obtain a version of the <fr:link href="jms-017D.xml" title="The matching relation for regular expressions" addr="jms-017D" type="local">matching relation</fr:link> between <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">strings</fr:link> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:link href="jms-0176.xml" title="Regular expressions (concrete syntax)" addr="jms-0176" type="local"><fr:em>concrete</fr:em> regular expressions</fr:link> by <fr:link href="jms-00IN.xml" title="Relational composite" addr="jms-00IN" type="local">relational composition</fr:link> with the (transpose of) the <fr:link href="jms-017B.xml" title="Precedence parsing for regular expressions" addr="jms-017B" type="local">parsing relation</fr:link>. Alternatively, we can simply <fr:em>write</fr:em> the concrete syntax as a mere notation (to be eliminated by the reader immediately) for the abstract syntax. In fact, that is what we will do in the future.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>11</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7404</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-017E</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-017E.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Examples of regular expression matching">Examples of regular expression matching</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Consider <fr:link href="jms-017D.xml" title="The matching relation for regular expressions" addr="jms-017D" type="local">regular expression matching</fr:link> over the alphabet <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ={\mathopen {}\left \{a,b\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\vert  b]]></fr:tex> is matched by each symbol in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a\vert  b)*]]></fr:tex> is matched every <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b(a\vert  b)*]]></fr:tex> is matched by any <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> that starts with a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[((a\vert  b)(a\vert  b))*]]></fr:tex> is matched by any <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> of even length over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\underline {\epsilon }\vert  a)(\underline {\epsilon }\vert  b)\vert  bb]]></fr:tex> is matched just by the <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">strings</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ab]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[bb]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varnothing  b\vert  a]]></fr:tex> is matched only by the symbol <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>11</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7405</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-017F</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-017F.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Questions about regular expression matching">Questions about regular expression matching</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Discussion</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Here are some questions for discussion.</fr:p>
                <fr:ol><fr:li>Is there an algorithm which, given a string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and a regular expression <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>, computes whether or not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>?</fr:li>
 <fr:li>In formulating the definition of regular expressions, have we missed out on some practically useful notions of pattern?</fr:li>
 <fr:li>Is there an algorithm that will compute whether two regular expressions generate the same <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">language</fr:link>?</fr:li>
 <fr:li>Is every <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> of generated by a regular expression?</fr:li></fr:ol>
                <fr:p>We will come back to these questions in subsequent lectures. In the meantime, we can say:</fr:p>
                <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:em>Is there an algorithm which, given a string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and a regular expression <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>, computes whether or not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>?</fr:em> Yes. One very simple way is to simply use the rules of <fr:link href="jms-017D.xml" title="The matching relation for regular expressions" addr="jms-017D" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-017D" /></fr:link> as a search algorithm, but this is not very efficient; better ways to decide regular expression matching can be achieved using <fr:em>finite automata</fr:em>, which we will study in the next lecture.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:em>In formulating the definition of regular expressions, have we missed out on some practically useful notions of pattern?</fr:em>
  Yes! For example, it can be useful to specify a <fr:em>range</fr:em> of symbols (including all symbols!) over an alphabet like most practical regular expression libraries allow. A more sophisticated example is complementation, where a <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\sim }(r)]]></fr:tex> if and only if it does <fr:em>not</fr:em> match <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>. We will ultimately see that the complement of any regular expression already exists—but it can be useful to include it as a built-in feature.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:em>Is there an algorithm that will compute whether two regular expressions generate the same <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">language</fr:link>?</fr:em> Yes, but we will need the theory of finite automata to see that this is the case.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:em>Is every <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> of generated by a regular expression?</fr:em> No: we will ultimately learn a technique, called the <fr:em>pumping lemma</fr:em> to find counter-examples.</fr:li></fr:ol>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
