          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Here are some questions for discussion.</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>Is there an algorithm which, given a string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and a regular expression <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>, computes whether or not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>?</fr:li>
 <fr:li>In formulating the definition of regular expressions, have we missed out on some practically useful notions of pattern?</fr:li>
 <fr:li>Is there an algorithm that will compute whether two regular expressions generate the same <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">language</fr:link>?</fr:li>
 <fr:li>Is every <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> of generated by a regular expression?</fr:li></fr:ol>
            <fr:p>We will come back to these questions in subsequent lectures. In the meantime, we can say:</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:em>Is there an algorithm which, given a string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and a regular expression <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>, computes whether or not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>?</fr:em> Yes. One very simple way is to simply use the rules of <fr:link href="jms-017D.xml" title="The matching relation for regular expressions" addr="jms-017D" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-017D" /></fr:link> as a search algorithm, but this is not very efficient; better ways to decide regular expression matching can be achieved using <fr:em>finite automata</fr:em>, which we will study in the next lecture.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:em>In formulating the definition of regular expressions, have we missed out on some practically useful notions of pattern?</fr:em>
  Yes! For example, it can be useful to specify a <fr:em>range</fr:em> of symbols (including all symbols!) over an alphabet like most practical regular expression libraries allow. A more sophisticated example is complementation, where a <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\sim }(r)]]></fr:tex> if and only if it does <fr:em>not</fr:em> match <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>. We will ultimately see that the complement of any regular expression already exists—but it can be useful to include it as a built-in feature.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:em>Is there an algorithm that will compute whether two regular expressions generate the same <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">language</fr:link>?</fr:em> Yes, but we will need the theory of finite automata to see that this is the case.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:em>Is every <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> of generated by a regular expression?</fr:em> No: we will ultimately learn a technique, called the <fr:em>pumping lemma</fr:em> to find counter-examples.</fr:li></fr:ol>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
